TY  - JOUR
AB  - This paper examines preferences toward particular classes of lottery pairs. We show how such concepts as prudence and temperance can be fully characterized by a preference relation over these lotteries. If preferences are defined in an expected-utility framework with differentiable utility, the direction of preference for a particular class of lottery pairs is equivalent to signing the $n^{th}$ derivative of the utility function. What makes our characterization appealing is its simplicity, which seems particularly amenable to experimentation.
